And then the other thing is that for very understandable reasons, it tends to be in those

19:47.220 --> 19:52.100
parts of the world that the electricity sectors are still most fossil fuels intensive.

19:52.100 --> 19:58.140
So here are some figures that just put a complexion on this that I think is important.

19:58.140 --> 20:02.780
So I live in Sweden, it's almost fully decarbonised, it's power sector.

20:02.780 --> 20:07.220
Something like 90% of electricity now is generated from non-carbon sources.

20:07.220 --> 20:13.660
I think it's like roughly 30, 30, 30 nuclear wind hydro, about 10% is natural gas.

20:13.700 --> 20:18.100
So Sweden's almost there on the power sector, at least.

20:18.100 --> 20:21.420
UK, Germany, US, quite a way behind that.

20:21.420 --> 20:24.820
Germany's pretty awful, lots of coal burning still.

20:24.820 --> 20:27.140
US, lots of coal and natural gas.

20:27.140 --> 20:28.340
UK, lots of natural gas.

20:28.340 --> 20:29.700
Scotland very good though.

20:29.700 --> 20:33.340
Yeah, we'll talk about Scotland because it's a big part of the story.

20:33.340 --> 20:38.780
So they're a way behind, but they're still a long way ahead of other parts of the world.

20:38.780 --> 20:41.900
China, 65% of electricity generation is coal.

20:41.900 --> 20:49.340
India, 75%, South Africa, 90%, other countries 95% to 98%.

20:49.340 --> 20:55.980
And so it's most urgent that investment in decarbonisation happens there.

20:55.980 --> 20:58.940
A, because their fossil fuel intent, very fossil fuel intensive.

20:58.940 --> 21:01.700
B, that's where energy demand growth is going to be concentrated.

21:01.700 --> 21:05.700
But that's where the challenge is greatest economically for reasons that we can talk about.

21:05.700 --> 21:08.140
And that's the real problem as I see it.

21:08.180 --> 21:10.780
So let's take an, again, an optimistic slant on this.

21:10.780 --> 21:14.340
Firstly, on China, I mean, China, again, we've got some great statistics.

21:14.340 --> 21:17.180
I'm sure you can bring it off the top of your head.

21:17.180 --> 21:23.460
For most of the last six, seven years, about 50% of sort of additional solar capacity

21:23.460 --> 21:26.580
being added worldwide is in China.

21:26.580 --> 21:28.980
It's a similar story with wind.

21:28.980 --> 21:29.300
Yep.

21:29.300 --> 21:31.060
It's blowing the United States out of the water.

21:31.060 --> 21:32.340
100%.

21:32.340 --> 21:34.220
Blowing the EU as well, but not quite as much.

21:34.220 --> 21:37.660
I mean, it's making it, you know, the US is a clown show compared to China.

21:37.660 --> 21:44.340
But obviously you have increasing demand, CO2 emissions per person still going up.

21:44.340 --> 21:51.660
But the optimistic story is this, CO2 emissions per person in China may reach a peak.

21:51.660 --> 21:55.620
Well, the plan was for 2030, but it's looking actually like the next couple of years,

21:55.620 --> 21:59.100
potentially, according to Xi.

21:59.100 --> 22:01.460
So that's one positive thing.

22:01.460 --> 22:02.140
Absolutely.

22:02.140 --> 22:07.020
Secondly, and this is probably where you're going to say that's completely wrong,

22:07.060 --> 22:10.700
there's this optimistic account of Africa, which is like,

22:10.700 --> 22:14.140
well, they didn't have landline connections, but they just, they skipped that bit

22:14.140 --> 22:18.020
and they did the mobile telephony and they're going to do the same with energy.

22:18.020 --> 22:20.460
They're going to skip, you know, national grids with fossil fuels.

22:20.460 --> 22:23.540
They're going to go straight to distributed solar.

22:23.540 --> 22:24.900
And on the one hand, that sounds absurd.

22:24.900 --> 22:27.620
But on the other hand, actually within the tropics,

22:27.620 --> 22:29.540
you do have an extraordinary amount of exposure to solar energy.

22:29.540 --> 22:30.100
Absolutely.

22:30.100 --> 22:32.260
It's a brilliant place to have it.

22:32.260 --> 22:34.340
So what's wrong with that account?

22:34.340 --> 22:38.660
An optimistic account of actually things are far better than the picture you're painting.

22:38.660 --> 22:39.060
Yeah.

22:39.060 --> 22:46.620
I mean, I think that both of those parts of the story have a strong degree of truth, actually.

22:46.620 --> 22:54.100
I think that China is a, you know, China's hugely paradoxical and for all sorts of different reasons.

22:54.100 --> 23:01.580
And right now, it's obviously the good news story on renewables,

23:01.580 --> 23:05.660
but it's also the bad news story on kind of new coal-fired plants as well,

23:05.660 --> 23:09.620
which is simply due to the fact, simply is probably the wrong word,

23:09.620 --> 23:14.060
but it's due to the fact that energy demand is growing still so strongly there,

23:14.060 --> 23:19.020
both from, you know, residential, commercial, industrial and so on.

23:19.020 --> 23:22.740
And so renewables in and of themselves are not proving sufficient for that,

23:22.740 --> 23:29.380
which is partly just a scale issue, but it's also partly about the different nature of the energy source.

23:29.420 --> 23:31.140
But China's important to talk about.

23:31.140 --> 23:39.580
And what I think is important is to understand the political economy of how it's doing things very differently to how we're doing it in the West.

23:39.580 --> 23:43.220
There's some commonalities, but there's some big important differences as well.

23:43.220 --> 23:47.500
I think on Africa, I think that is the big hope, actually.

23:47.500 --> 23:57.900
And, you know, I see conflicting accounts about how credible that story is about

23:57.900 --> 24:06.220
the extent to which it will be possible to build out a clean energy future there

24:06.220 --> 24:10.580
that does kind of leapfrog the kind of historical problems that we've,

24:10.580 --> 24:15.300
that are kind of almost a sunk cost here in the West,

24:15.300 --> 24:21.060
where we have a very kind of centralized grid-based energy system,

24:21.060 --> 24:26.380
which locks us into a certain kind of future that may not be necessary in Africa, as you say.

24:26.380 --> 24:32.380
If it moves towards more distributed energy resources, then maybe it's possible to do that.

24:32.380 --> 24:38.740
I mean, I think there are reasons to think both positively and negatively about that story.

24:38.740 --> 24:44.740
I think right now it's too early to tell which direction it's going.

24:44.740 --> 24:52.540
But possibly that's true, and I think that will be very, very important.

24:52.540 --> 24:58.140
And let's not forget that, you know, just, I mean, I think there's a connection between those two stories, right, that we just talked about.

24:58.140 --> 25:05.820
So if you look at what China did in 2023, when it was, you know, set all kinds of records for new renewable installation,

25:05.820 --> 25:10.940
something like 30% of that renewable installation in China was rooftop solar.

25:10.940 --> 25:17.620
So it wasn't commercial, large-scale, industrial power plants, wind and solar farms.

25:17.620 --> 25:20.500
It was rooftop domestic solar, 30%.

25:20.540 --> 25:26.340
Huge. All sorts of state subsidy necessary for that, but that's fine.

25:26.340 --> 25:30.980
So part of the China story is precisely that distributed energy story,

25:30.980 --> 25:34.820
which one would hope would be replicated in Africa as well.

25:34.820 --> 25:36.100
And Vietnam as well, right?

25:36.100 --> 25:39.780
Again, it's one of these stories in Europe and the West we don't really hear.

25:39.780 --> 25:43.660
Like, there is a heroic effort going into solar right now in Vietnam.

25:43.660 --> 25:44.100
There is.

25:44.100 --> 25:47.820
And it's not on our radar, and we think in Europe we're doing everything.

25:47.820 --> 25:52.580
You know, we've got, you go in Germany or Italy, you might see some solar cells.

25:52.580 --> 25:53.140
Great.

25:53.140 --> 25:56.580
But in Vietnam, they're doing what those countries did in 20 years.

25:56.580 --> 25:58.260
They're doing it in three or four years.

25:58.260 --> 25:59.180
Yeah, absolutely.

25:59.180 --> 26:04.500
And obviously, I mean, to take, I mean, China is the best example of this.

26:04.500 --> 26:12.460
But the reason that China can and is doing things at a much more rapid clip

26:12.500 --> 26:17.580
and on a much, much greater scale than is happening in the West

26:17.580 --> 26:21.140
is simply because it's essentially a state project, right?

26:21.140 --> 26:28.420
I mean, to take wind, something like 95% of the wind deployment sector,

26:28.420 --> 26:33.260
by which I mean the entities that are involved, not on the manufacturing side,

26:33.260 --> 26:36.620
building the turbines and building the cells and modules,

26:36.620 --> 26:39.900
although it's not hugely dissimilar there, but on the deployment side,

26:39.900 --> 26:42.860
by which I mean developing the wind and solar farms,

26:42.860 --> 26:46.140
owning and operating them and selling the electricity that they generate,

26:46.140 --> 26:50.460
something like 95% of that is state-owned enterprises.

26:50.460 --> 26:54.820
They are being financed by state-owned banks

26:54.820 --> 27:00.460
who are themselves having their debts subsidized by the state-owned central bank.

27:00.460 --> 27:05.060
And all of these entities are, at least if my understanding of this is correct,

27:05.060 --> 27:08.820
and it's a second-hand understanding based on kind of the work of China experts,

27:08.860 --> 27:11.260
you know, heck of a lot more about it than I do,

27:11.260 --> 27:16.260
all of these entities are only, what's the best word to you,

27:16.260 --> 27:21.180
modestly being driven by profit motives of one kind or another.

27:21.180 --> 27:28.300
They are, to one degree or another, working at the behest of provincial

27:28.300 --> 27:31.620
and or central government in China.

27:31.620 --> 27:36.100
They are being directed very substantially in terms of what they're doing now.

27:36.100 --> 27:39.100
And if you have the willpower and if you have the resources

27:39.100 --> 27:43.100
and you have the determination and the political intent

27:43.100 --> 27:47.140
to do that sort of thing on a huge scale and quickly,

27:47.140 --> 27:48.860
well, you can do that.

27:48.860 --> 27:54.940
But in the West, where we are essentially relying on the private sector to do this

27:54.940 --> 27:57.620
and we are relying on the kind of quote-unquote

27:57.620 --> 28:01.540
coordinating mechanisms of markets to do this,

28:01.540 --> 28:03.460
it's an entirely different project.

28:03.460 --> 28:09.300
You're expecting, you know, the independent decisions of thousands of different entities

28:09.300 --> 28:14.740
to kind of add up to this very complicated thing that we call a transition.

28:14.740 --> 28:18.420
And not surprisingly, it's not really happening in the same way

28:18.420 --> 28:21.380
that it is where you have a top-down approach to this

28:21.380 --> 28:25.860
that can be very, very coordinated and very, very joined up

28:25.860 --> 28:29.180
because you have one entity that is overseeing all of it.

28:29.180 --> 28:32.860
I mean, we had this debate recently on the Var Alive, Michael and I,

28:32.900 --> 28:35.500
and he was saying China is a capitalist society.

28:35.500 --> 28:37.260
And I said, it's not a capitalist society.

28:37.260 --> 28:39.660
It's a market society.

28:39.660 --> 28:41.780
But there's a huge difference in that in a capitalist society.

28:41.780 --> 28:42.540
I mean, I totally agree.

28:42.540 --> 28:44.340
And even then, is it a market society?

28:44.340 --> 28:45.460
I mean, even this is the debate.

28:45.460 --> 28:48.580
I mean, if you look at what's going on in the energy sector,

28:48.580 --> 28:52.860
I would be quite reticent to call the mechanisms

28:52.860 --> 28:58.100
whereby and the context within which electricity is bought and sold,

28:58.100 --> 29:00.580
markets in anything like the shape of which we're used to.

29:00.700 --> 29:04.260
The firms that are building, you know, the firms that are making the PV cells,

29:04.260 --> 29:07.460
which would take over the world if we weren't imposing tariffs on them.

29:07.460 --> 29:10.180
That is all being done by private actors in competition.

29:10.180 --> 29:12.740
And I think this is something that Michael and I really discredent.

29:12.740 --> 29:15.060
And I said, it's a market society.

29:15.060 --> 29:17.420
But the point is, it's not capitalist because Eric E. Lee,

29:17.420 --> 29:19.180
who's a political scientist, Chinese political scientist,

29:19.180 --> 29:22.580
he said, we're not a capitalist society because, yes, we have markets,

29:22.580 --> 29:27.020
but capital does not determine how our society allocates resources.

29:27.020 --> 29:28.700
The interests of capital are not so enormous

29:28.740 --> 29:30.620
with the interests of the ruling class.

29:30.620 --> 29:33.820
Our ruling class has national political priorities, which sometimes...

29:33.820 --> 29:34.820
100%.

29:34.820 --> 29:36.260
Which is odds with capital.

29:36.260 --> 29:38.620
And I think for people in the West, that's a really hard thing to engage with.

29:38.620 --> 29:39.620
It is.

29:39.620 --> 29:42.900
You have markets, but you don't allow capital to determine political priorities.

29:42.900 --> 29:46.740
So I was on a panel recently and there was a sociologist,

29:46.740 --> 29:50.460
a Chinese sociologist who works in the US called Karl Chan,

29:50.460 --> 29:52.740
who's been doing a lot of really interesting research

29:52.740 --> 29:54.860
about Chinese state-owned enterprises.

29:54.860 --> 29:58.220
And I think the concept he uses to try to capture what it is they do,

29:58.220 --> 30:00.340
I think he calls it managed competition.

30:00.340 --> 30:01.180
What's the chap's name?

30:01.180 --> 30:03.340
Kyle Chan, C-H-A-N.

30:03.340 --> 30:08.260
And it's a really evocative and useful way of thinking about this,

30:08.260 --> 30:11.740
that it's just not competition in the way we think about it.

30:11.740 --> 30:16.380
It's a managed process towards a particular end

30:16.380 --> 30:20.460
to which competition is being mobilized in some way,

30:20.460 --> 30:24.500
but only in a very limited capacity to make sure that these things are happening.

30:25.340 --> 30:29.980
It was quite interesting hearing basically Chinese automotive manufacturers,

30:29.980 --> 30:32.220
they were being asked, are you gunning for the US?

30:32.220 --> 30:33.140
Are you gunning for Tesla?

30:33.140 --> 30:36.260
And they're like, we have enough problems with our own people back home,

30:36.260 --> 30:40.660
like BYD are terrified of the next four or five companies beneath them.

30:40.660 --> 30:43.260
And of course, if you look at that from a sort of classical,

30:43.260 --> 30:46.700
a neoclassical sort of political economy perspective,

30:46.700 --> 30:48.660
you'd be like, well, those are exactly the sorts of incentives

30:48.660 --> 30:51.860
which are meant to be driving firms and industrialists.

30:52.260 --> 30:56.780
And it's so strange that China and its firms are talking in that language.

30:56.780 --> 30:59.500
And yet, the US is talking in a very protectionist language,

30:59.500 --> 31:01.100
he's talking about national champions.

31:01.100 --> 31:02.900
China is not talking about national champions.

31:02.900 --> 31:04.620
No, no, no, no, no.

31:04.620 --> 31:06.860
No, because they've already, they're already the champions.

31:06.860 --> 31:09.620
They're the international champions.

31:09.620 --> 31:11.660
Yeah, this is another one, this is a bit of an aside,

31:11.660 --> 31:14.860
but again, you're going to be a lot more familiar with the reality of this

31:14.860 --> 31:16.540
because you do all these academic panels and whatnot.

31:16.540 --> 31:19.380
But we have a friend here at Navarro who sometimes works with us

31:19.380 --> 31:23.660
on sort of helping us out, kind of like a consultant guy.

31:23.660 --> 31:26.660
And they were recently in, I think, Vietnam.

31:26.660 --> 31:30.140
And they kept on seeing all these brands they just never heard of.

31:30.140 --> 31:32.740
And then they were like, what's that? Google that, Google that, Google that.

31:32.740 --> 31:36.060
And then they said, look, after a while, I realized that like the world's number one,

31:36.060 --> 31:41.220
two, three producer for dozens of, you know, commodities, which I've granted,

31:41.220 --> 31:42.940
they're all East Asian, right?

31:42.940 --> 31:44.860
You know, they're Chinese or if they're not Chinese,

31:44.860 --> 31:47.940
they'll be Japanese or Taiwanese or and I was like, yeah.

31:47.940 --> 31:50.180
We do live in a little closeted world in some respects.

31:50.180 --> 31:51.900
But I think Europeans don't realize.

31:51.900 --> 31:53.860
No, of course they don't. No, absolutely not.

31:53.860 --> 31:55.100
Very stretch.

31:55.100 --> 31:58.420
So you're optimistic, but also in a way pessimistic about China.

31:58.420 --> 32:01.260
I suppose one good way of looking at China is

32:01.260 --> 32:03.660
we would be really screwed if they weren't doing all the things.

32:03.660 --> 32:08.300
They would be. I mean, the way, I mean, not least in terms of, I mean,

32:08.300 --> 32:11.260
there's for one thing, there's the fact that they are making progress

32:11.260 --> 32:12.580
domestically on renewables, right?

32:12.580 --> 32:13.380
Fantastic.

32:13.380 --> 32:17.460
But there's also the fact that let's not forget that it's unimaginable

32:17.460 --> 32:22.820
that in places like Europe, that to the extent that it's happened so far,

32:22.820 --> 32:26.180
that the energy transition, the decarbonization of power sector

32:26.180 --> 32:33.540
would have gone as far, as fast and at such a low, relatively low cost as it has.

32:33.540 --> 32:38.020
Were it not from the fact that it's China that drove down the cost of the technologies, right?

32:38.020 --> 32:42.340
I mean, there's no, there's no way it would have gone as far as fast or at such low cost

32:42.340 --> 32:44.100
without China doing what it's done.

32:44.180 --> 32:49.780
We've, we collectively have been benefiting environmentally and economically

32:49.780 --> 32:52.180
from what China's been doing for the last 15 to 20 years.

32:52.180 --> 32:53.540
That is such a good point.

32:53.540 --> 32:57.100
So people are saying, and we'll talk about obviously that the fallen price for renewables,

32:57.100 --> 32:59.500
how it's competitive with fossil fuels, and a big part of that,

32:59.500 --> 33:03.460
that disinflationary pressure is the fact that stuff is being manufactured in China.

33:03.460 --> 33:04.860
Almost all about China.

33:04.860 --> 33:06.180
And that's very rarely in the conversation.

33:06.180 --> 33:07.100
No, no, no, no.

33:07.100 --> 33:10.060
Because we talk about energy security, but we can have, we can have our cake and eat it.

33:10.060 --> 33:12.220
It can be cheap and it can be energy secure.

33:12.220 --> 33:12.940
Hold on a second.

33:12.940 --> 33:15.180
It's cheap because it's not made here.

33:15.180 --> 33:16.940
It's actually made outside of the planet.

33:16.940 --> 33:17.740
Yeah, absolutely.

33:17.740 --> 33:20.500
And obviously what's going on in the U.S. right now, and again,

33:20.500 --> 33:24.780
there's a bit of a tangent, but it's important, is that the Biden administration

33:24.780 --> 33:39.060
is trying to thread the needle between not wanting to entirely give up those economic gains

33:39.060 --> 33:41.980
that have been delivered and continued to be delivered by China.

33:41.980 --> 33:44.460
While at the same time benefiting domestic industry.

33:44.460 --> 33:48.900
So they're trying to play this delicate game where they're like saying to the renewable energy developers,

33:48.900 --> 33:54.580
look, if you, if you source your technology locally, rather than from China,

33:54.580 --> 34:02.180
from local manufacturers, you get an extra 10% credit on your, on your renewables development.

34:02.180 --> 34:06.260
And, but I, you know, based on the conversations I've had with people in the U.S.,

34:06.260 --> 34:10.980
it's still entirely unclear whether that incremental benefit is proving sufficient

34:10.980 --> 34:16.580
to persuade them to source locally or whether it still makes economic sense for them to source from China.

34:16.580 --> 34:17.500
Yeah, they don't know yet.

34:17.500 --> 34:19.620
Well, because you have these recent tariffs announced by Biden, right?

34:19.620 --> 34:20.780
Yeah, that was, that was a lot.

34:20.780 --> 34:21.500
They've changed it.

34:21.500 --> 34:23.300
They've introduced some new tariffs last week.

34:23.300 --> 34:27.540
So 100% on automotive, you know, so electric vehicles will have 100% tariffs.

34:27.540 --> 34:32.380
So if I'm buying a BYD car and it's $30,000 in China, I'm going to have to pay $30,000 tariff on it.

34:32.380 --> 34:33.580
Yep, exactly.

34:33.580 --> 34:35.500
And I still think that car might be competitive.

34:35.500 --> 34:36.460
Yeah, it could well be.

34:36.460 --> 34:38.340
Which is the terrifying thing for the U.S. car industry.

34:38.340 --> 34:39.420
Yeah, no, absolutely.

34:39.460 --> 34:45.540
Yeah, so they're, they're playing a very challenging game over there, which, which, which, I mean, I understand that game politically.

34:46.380 --> 34:49.940
I mean, it makes, it makes it's easy to understand where they're coming from.

34:50.780 --> 34:51.580
Politically, yes.

34:51.580 --> 34:52.860
But then you can't say climate change...

34:52.860 --> 34:54.780
Oh, not necessarily economically, environmentally, no.

34:54.780 --> 34:58.420
You can't say climate change is existential, but then put 50% tariffs on PV cells.

34:58.420 --> 34:58.860
No.

34:58.860 --> 35:00.180
Well, you don't believe that then, do you?

35:00.180 --> 35:09.380
But then, but then the whole, I mean, let's be honest about this, but the whole, the whole climate policy,

35:09.620 --> 35:21.020
thing in the U.S. perspective is entirely contradictory, by which I mean, you know, I think the Inflation Reduction Act is actually pretty good policy for the, for the most part.

35:22.060 --> 35:32.100
And I think that given the, given the political conditions under which Biden has been operating, it was probably about as good as, as he could have got through at the time.

35:33.100 --> 35:37.980
And yet, you know, one day Biden will be extolling the benefits of the Inflation Reduction Act.

35:37.980 --> 35:57.380
And yet the very next day, he'll be like calling out OPEC for introducing new production quotas to dampen oil and gas production, because Biden is concerned that that, that constraint in global oil and gas supply will have, you know, will put the price of gasoline up 3 cents.

35:57.380 --> 35:59.700
And it means that he won't, he won't get voted into power.

35:59.700 --> 36:01.660
So he's telling OPEC to open the pumps.

36:01.980 --> 36:05.740
So it's just like, it's the most contradictory thing imaginable.

36:06.100 --> 36:17.980
And, and, and that's the thing I think we have to grapple with, is that the whole kind of U.S. political, economic, ecological complex is fundamentally driven with contradiction.

36:19.100 --> 36:22.340
And you compare that to Europe, which for the most part has proportional representation.

36:22.980 --> 36:26.140
At least you can build in a consensus around a certain policy direction.

36:26.540 --> 36:27.060
That's true.

36:27.100 --> 36:31.020
Whereas in the U.S., you have like, I mean, it's crazy, you have Biden saying, I'm a green champion.

36:31.020 --> 36:37.580
And then, and then, but then, and it's, and you understand why they'll be saying, look, if inflation is 5% in November, we're out, we're gone.

36:37.620 --> 36:38.220
100%.

36:38.340 --> 36:38.620
Right.

36:38.620 --> 36:39.380
And they know that.

36:40.260 --> 36:44.660
And so you have these wildly diverging policies, messages.

36:44.700 --> 36:50.820
And we, we in the West, but especially in America, live very carbon intensive lifestyles.

36:50.980 --> 36:55.900
And so inflation is, is a carboniferous phenomenon in the U.S.

36:55.940 --> 36:57.620
more than anywhere else.

36:57.900 --> 36:59.460
And it's really important to remember that.

36:59.740 --> 37:04.540
So the inflation discussion is a significant part of carbon discussion in the U.S.

37:04.620 --> 37:07.500
And it's very, very important to remember that politically as well as economically.

37:08.220 --> 37:15.260
Going back to Europe, you mentioned the Inflation Reduction Act, the IRA Act, IRA Act.

37:15.260 --> 37:20.500
I can't say that without, yeah, having memories of growing up in Croydon in the 1970s.

37:20.620 --> 37:30.860
And, you know, Biden's, Biden's famous Irish heritage, I do find it, I'm sure he probably finds it quite, you know, you know, interesting.

37:30.900 --> 37:31.300
Yes.

37:33.300 --> 37:35.860
You got the IRA Act, you got the CHIPS Act, that's not really related.

37:35.860 --> 37:48.980
And at the same time as the IRA Act, which is this, you know, huge amount of money basically going into reshore lots of manufacturing in the UK, but also it's ostensibly about a decarbonisation agenda.

37:49.420 --> 37:51.780
At the same time, you have, obviously, Russia, Ukraine.

37:52.340 --> 37:55.460
And what you're seeing right now is that sort of amazing statistic in the FT recently.

37:55.460 --> 38:00.620
I think it's like 45% of German manufacturing companies are looking at setting up shop in the U.S.

38:01.180 --> 38:07.340
Because energy in Germany compared to the U.S. is six times more expensive, six times more.

38:07.340 --> 38:08.300
Wow, I hadn't seen that statistic.

38:08.300 --> 38:11.060
Yeah, industrial energy, I think it was five to six times more.

38:11.100 --> 38:11.380
Wow.

38:11.420 --> 38:16.420
But then on top of that, you have the IRA, you know, subsidies or whatever, tax, you know, breaks and what not.

38:16.740 --> 38:23.140
All of a sudden, you know, these industrial firms that have been in Germany for like 800 years thinking, am I going to Texas?

38:23.580 --> 38:27.900
Germany really isn't heading in a good direction in any sense, in any shape or form right now, is it?

38:27.900 --> 38:30.060
So, yeah, okay, so explain that.

38:30.060 --> 38:33.780
So what, and where does U.S. policies fit on this?

38:33.780 --> 38:41.900
So is that, is that, is that an intentional effort by the United States government to basically say, you know what, we're going to reindustrialise on the back of deindustrialisation in Germany?

38:42.060 --> 38:43.140
Or is it not that deep?

38:43.380 --> 38:44.780
Am I being too conspiratorial?

38:44.780 --> 38:57.980
I'm not sure it's that deep, but certainly on the manufacturing side, U.S. policymakers have been, have been making an active effort to woo European companies, for sure.

38:58.140 --> 39:01.940
And not just on the manufacturing side, but also on the renewable energy development side.

39:02.020 --> 39:14.660
They've, you know, they've been trying to get the Iberdrohlers and the Orstedts and so on, much more interested in the U.S. as a place for investment in new, in new wind and solar power, as well as the manufacturing side of the business.

39:14.860 --> 39:16.700
But I'm not sure it's, I'm not sure it's that deep.

39:17.860 --> 39:28.740
But, you know, the EU, sorry, has been through, you know, a very difficult few years on the energy front in a way that the U.S. largely avoided.

39:29.980 --> 39:32.660
And I think there are, there are still lingering effects from that.

39:32.660 --> 39:41.860
And it's important to think about what's going on in Germany in relation to what happened in 2021 to 2022, which, which didn't really happen in the U.S.

39:42.860 --> 39:58.500
The energy crisis was a, was a phenomenon that was, it wasn't limited to the EU, but to the extent that it was significant outside the EU, it was, it was significant more to the East, not least in China than it was in the U.S.

39:59.500 --> 40:09.500
So the, the EU occupies this kind of strange sort of third provisional position in the kind of game between China and the U.S.

40:09.500 --> 40:17.500
The EU is in this uncertain position where it seems to be neither one thing or the other.

40:17.500 --> 40:27.500
It doesn't seem to be in a position to be calling any shots, but it's also not reacting as far as I can tell in the kind of deeply protectionist way that the U.S. has reacted.

40:29.500 --> 40:30.500
Yeah. So it's interesting.

40:30.500 --> 40:39.500
There was a great quote a year or two ago, basically saying that the energy crisis of, you know, 2022-2023, was it 2022-2022?

40:39.500 --> 40:40.500
21-22.

40:40.500 --> 40:41.500
21-22.

40:41.500 --> 40:42.500
Yeah.

40:42.500 --> 40:47.500
It's, you know, post-Covid, but also, you know, in relation to Germany in particular, post-Ukraine war.

40:47.500 --> 40:52.500
And they said, look, the last several years have basically brought into focus that there are two kinds of countries.

40:52.500 --> 40:54.500
Those with energy and those without.

40:54.500 --> 40:55.500
Yeah.

40:56.500 --> 40:59.500
You know, go massive on nuclear renewables, coal.

40:59.500 --> 41:02.500
The U.S. is where we have tons of energy anyway.

41:02.500 --> 41:07.500
And Europe doesn't have any energy, but it's not adopted a sort of a strategy like you say.

41:07.500 --> 41:15.500
No. I mean, Germany was the most extreme example of sort of essentially relying on Russia for energy.

41:15.500 --> 41:24.500
And that was true to a lesser extent, but also not to an insignificant extent in other parts of Europe as well.

41:24.500 --> 41:36.500
I mean, it just, I mean, it's, in that context, it is worth going back to China and the question of trying to understand its investment,

41:36.500 --> 41:44.500
that kind of hybrid state capitalist investment that it's been undertaking in its renewables industry,

41:44.500 --> 41:48.500
both the manufacturing side and the deployment side in the last couple of decades,

41:48.500 --> 41:51.500
and to think, well, what kind of strategy is that?

41:51.500 --> 42:03.500
And it's kind of a three-fold strategy by which I mean it's been partly a strategy that is about environmentalism.

42:03.500 --> 42:10.500
It's been partly a strategy which is an industrial strategy, trying to build global champions,

42:10.500 --> 42:15.500
global leadership in a particular sector, but it's also been a strategy about energy security.

42:15.500 --> 42:24.500
And by my understanding, it's the reverse order, actually, that the energy security was the kind of the main strategy

42:24.500 --> 42:31.500
and arguably still is the main strategy, then industrial strategy, and that the environmental part of it, I mean, it's become more important.

42:31.500 --> 42:34.500
20 years ago, it wasn't a significant part of the strategy.

42:34.500 --> 42:40.500
But even today, my suspicion is it's still not the first of those three and maybe not even the second of those three.

42:40.500 --> 42:42.500
And it's been about energy security.

42:42.500 --> 42:48.500
And so what happened in Europe, I mean, it's a different slant on the same question,

42:48.500 --> 42:53.500
but what happened in 2022 was there was a bit of a fillip in renewables investment in Europe.

42:53.500 --> 42:59.500
And a lot of people were saying, oh, this is further evidence of the fact that renewables are forging ahead

42:59.500 --> 43:02.500
because they're very, very cheap and they're economically competitive.

43:02.500 --> 43:04.500
And no, that wasn't really what happened.

43:04.500 --> 43:05.500
It was about energy security, right?

43:05.500 --> 43:11.500
If you have renewable and solar power, you're not reliant on importing fuel from overseas.

43:11.500 --> 43:14.500
You're not reliant on a rush or whoever else it might be.

43:14.500 --> 43:17.500
So I think it was an energy security issue that was driving that investment.

43:17.500 --> 43:20.500
What you just said is the crux of the book.

43:20.500 --> 43:22.500
And we'll get to that in a moment about the price.

43:22.500 --> 43:24.500
Yeah, we haven't really got to the book yet.

43:24.500 --> 43:27.500
No, it's critical because it's not about prices.

43:27.500 --> 43:32.500
We're getting to a point of price parity with regards to fossil fuels and renewables, but that's not the point.

43:32.500 --> 43:34.500
But particularly on Europe.

43:34.500 --> 43:35.500
Yes.

43:35.500 --> 43:43.500
I mean, that was the, you know, what we saw in 2022, 2023 was 101 think pieces about finally Europe is on the stage.

43:43.500 --> 43:45.500
Not only was it meant to remilitarize.

43:45.500 --> 43:46.500
Okay, what's happening there?

43:46.500 --> 43:48.500
It was meant to be rebuilding its domestic industry.

43:48.500 --> 43:50.500
It's doing the opposite, actually.

43:50.500 --> 43:54.500
It was also meant to be getting serious about renewals and nuclear energy.

43:54.500 --> 43:55.500
Yes.

43:55.500 --> 43:56.500
Not just upticks.

43:56.500 --> 43:59.500
And there has been much progress made and there is progress is being made.

43:59.500 --> 44:02.500
But it's not decarbonizing as quickly as we were told.

44:02.500 --> 44:03.500
No.

44:03.500 --> 44:04.500
Why is that?

44:04.500 --> 44:05.500
Russia?

44:05.500 --> 44:06.500
Russia's gone.

44:06.500 --> 44:07.500
Yeah.

44:07.500 --> 44:08.500
For the near future.

44:08.500 --> 44:15.500
And Germany's industrial prowess is literally, well, not entirely based on, but it was significantly based on cheap Russian energy.

44:15.500 --> 44:23.500
That's now gone, but there doesn't seem to be the political leadership in places like Germany to say, you know what, we now need to build a ton of wind, solar, nuclear.

44:23.500 --> 44:25.500
And you've got a green-red coalition there.

44:25.500 --> 44:30.500
You think, well, this should be the perfect set of circumstances for Germany to become a world leader in renewable energy.

44:30.500 --> 44:31.500
Yeah.

44:31.500 --> 44:32.500
So it's not happening.

44:32.500 --> 44:33.500
No, it's not.

44:33.500 --> 44:34.500
Why?

44:34.500 --> 44:58.500
So the narrative that you will typically hear about this, across the board actually politically and almost analytically as well, but certainly from both left and right, is that the problem is found in the realm of, for want of a better kind of label, politics and planning and bureaucracy.

44:58.500 --> 45:12.500
You'll have seen a thousand think pieces saying, look, the problem is that there's all this money waiting to go into renewables, but it's being held up by, you know, obstructionist local planning authorities.

45:12.500 --> 45:16.500
It's being held up by slow processes to get planning permission.

45:16.500 --> 45:19.500
It's being held up by long queues to get grid connections.

45:19.500 --> 45:21.500
It's being held up by nimbyism.

45:21.500 --> 45:22.500
And you know what?

45:22.500 --> 45:24.500
It is held up by all of those things.

45:24.500 --> 45:25.500
Absolutely.

45:25.500 --> 45:35.500
However, the other crucial part of that key of that main dominant narrative about this says what it's not being held up by is the economics.

45:35.500 --> 45:46.500
The economics has been solved because the price of generating electricity from solar and wind has come down sharply historically.

45:47.500 --> 46:01.500
And it has, over time, to a point of where, as you said, it's as cheap or often in many places even cheaper to generate solar and wind power than it is by burning natural gas or coal.

46:01.500 --> 46:05.500
So that's the key narrative is that it's all these other things.

46:05.500 --> 46:06.500
It's not the economics.

46:06.500 --> 46:10.500
My argument in the book is that, yes, it's all those other things, but it's also the economics.

46:10.500 --> 46:29.500
And the argument there is that the thinking specifically on the question of generating price, which is what all those think pieces do, and they reproduce the same charts showing the same cost curves coming down over time, is the wrong prism through which to think about it.

46:29.500 --> 46:37.500
And that we can understand much more about the industry and about why things are going too slowly if we focus on the question of profitability rather than price.

46:37.500 --> 46:39.500
So that's the argument I made.

46:39.500 --> 46:42.500
And so it's a complex, as you said, right at the outset.

46:42.500 --> 46:43.500
There's a lot of detail in it.

46:43.500 --> 46:44.500
It's quite wonky.

46:44.500 --> 46:45.500
It's quite complex.

46:45.500 --> 46:50.500
But the actual main argument is really straightforward, which is this.

46:50.500 --> 46:57.500
It's like, in profitability terms, renewables deployment is actually quite a problematic proposition.

46:57.500 --> 47:00.500
And I'll explain what I mean by that in a second.

47:01.500 --> 47:09.500
And that's a problem because we're relying on the private sector and the private sector is driven above all else by profitability expectations.

47:09.500 --> 47:17.500
If its expectations are on profitability are not adequate, it will not invest or it will not invest on the sufficient sale.

47:17.500 --> 47:23.500
So my argument is like, you need to understand that, A, we are relying mainly on solar and wind.

47:23.500 --> 47:31.500
So yes, there are countries in which there's much more of a role being given to nuclear and even in some countries, geothermal and hydro and so on.

47:31.500 --> 47:37.500
But for the most part, the world is kind of betting the house on solar and wind to a significant extent.

47:37.500 --> 47:45.500
And second, the world is banking on the private sector, not China, but elsewhere in the world, government policy is not to do it itself.

47:45.500 --> 47:48.500
It's to say, we expect you, the private sector, to do it.

47:48.500 --> 47:55.500
We will nudge you in the right direction through various incentives and subsidy mechanisms on where you're not doing it quickly enough.

47:55.500 --> 47:58.500
We'll provide you that help, but we're not going to do it.

47:58.500 --> 48:00.500
You're going to do it. We're expecting you to do it.

48:00.500 --> 48:08.500
That's fine if the private sector consistently sees sufficient profitability in that proposition to do it quickly and at scale.

48:08.500 --> 48:09.500
But it doesn't.

48:09.500 --> 48:12.500
And you talk to people in the industry and they're like, no, of course not.

48:13.500 --> 48:15.500
But policymakers are completely deaf to this.

48:15.500 --> 48:22.500
And I think for all sorts of reasons, but partly because they've been persuaded by those simplistic arguments about falling prices.

48:22.500 --> 48:27.500
And to them, it's like, well, surely if the prices have fallen, the profits must be there.

48:27.500 --> 48:28.500
The profits must be going up.

48:28.500 --> 48:30.500
But it's just not true.

48:30.500 --> 48:33.500
It's a problematic industry in terms of profitability expectations.

48:33.500 --> 48:36.500
And that's the kind of core of the book as to why that is.

48:36.500 --> 48:38.500
And it is a bit of a wonky book.

48:38.500 --> 48:39.500
We like wonky books.

48:39.500 --> 48:40.500
Oh, yeah.

48:40.500 --> 48:41.500
Well, yeah, I hope so.

48:41.500 --> 48:42.500
We love wonky books.

48:42.500 --> 48:44.500
I mean, don't let that put you off.

48:44.500 --> 48:47.500
I think particularly, look, for anybody who wants to know the subject well.

48:47.500 --> 48:51.500
And the point is, like you say, the core proposition at the heart of the book is a very important one.

48:51.500 --> 48:53.500
And, you know, it's like...

48:53.500 --> 48:55.500
I think it's really important.

48:55.500 --> 48:56.500
Yeah.

48:56.500 --> 49:01.500
It's like the arrow that goes through, you know, Harold Goodwin's Anziah Hastings.

49:01.500 --> 49:02.500
You know, it's...

49:02.500 --> 49:03.500
That's it.

49:03.500 --> 49:05.500
It's game over for that worldview of...

49:05.500 --> 49:10.500
Well, actually, private firms, the private sector with the profit motive can solve the climate crisis.

49:10.500 --> 49:11.500
Exactly.

49:11.500 --> 49:12.500
They can't.

49:12.500 --> 49:13.500
It's not about costs.

49:13.500 --> 49:14.500
It's about...

49:14.500 --> 49:15.500
It's not about prices or other.

49:15.500 --> 49:16.500
It's about profit.

49:16.500 --> 49:17.500
Yeah.

49:17.500 --> 49:20.500
And obviously, profitability is shaped by generating prices.

49:20.500 --> 49:22.500
That's part of the equation, but it's not the totality.

49:22.500 --> 49:23.500
That's the issue.

49:23.500 --> 49:24.500
Yeah.

49:24.500 --> 49:29.500
And I actually feel like there are some similarities here with the debates I've had recently with

49:29.500 --> 49:34.500
people in regards to, you know, privatised utilities of things like mail, rail, water.

49:34.500 --> 49:37.500
And they're arguing for, you know, the private sector should control these.

49:37.500 --> 49:42.500
And I go, look, best-case scenario, best-case scenario, they're very low margin.

49:42.500 --> 49:44.500
You want it to be very competitive.

49:44.500 --> 49:46.500
They're very physically hard to administer.

49:46.500 --> 49:47.500
They're not very exciting.

49:47.500 --> 49:48.500
No.

49:48.500 --> 49:51.500
Like, why do you want the private sector here?

49:51.500 --> 49:53.500
And they're also very important.

49:53.500 --> 49:54.500
Go...

49:54.500 --> 49:55.500
100%.

49:55.500 --> 49:57.500
Go make, like, shirts.

49:57.500 --> 49:58.500
I mean, it's true, right?

49:58.500 --> 49:59.500
No.

49:59.500 --> 50:00.500
Or glasses or mobile phones or...

50:00.500 --> 50:01.500
Come up with a coffee machine.

50:01.500 --> 50:02.500
Exactly.

50:02.500 --> 50:05.500
Or like a scalable social network where you can 10X your...

50:05.500 --> 50:06.500
Knock yourself out.

50:06.500 --> 50:07.500
Do you see something different and better?

50:07.500 --> 50:08.500
Yeah.

50:08.500 --> 50:09.500
Yes.

50:09.500 --> 50:10.500
Water can't do that.

50:10.500 --> 50:11.500
No.

50:11.500 --> 50:12.500
And I feel like renewables are in a similar situation.

50:12.500 --> 50:13.500
100%.

50:13.500 --> 50:14.500
It's just a low margin thing.

50:14.500 --> 50:15.500
It's just electrons.

50:15.500 --> 50:16.500
Yeah.

50:16.500 --> 50:17.500
Just leave it alone.

50:17.500 --> 50:18.500
I know.

50:18.500 --> 50:19.500
I know.

50:19.500 --> 50:20.500
Yeah.

50:20.500 --> 50:21.500
It's bizarre.

50:21.500 --> 50:22.500
And the thing is, right...

50:22.500 --> 50:23.500
I think the other thing to...

50:23.500 --> 50:29.500
You know, one of the ways I think it's useful to think about this is that governments,

50:29.500 --> 50:34.500
for very understandable reasons, going back to what we were talking about inflation, they

50:34.500 --> 50:37.500
want electricity to be affordable.

50:37.500 --> 50:38.500
They want to be cheap.

50:38.500 --> 50:39.500
Rightly so.

50:39.500 --> 50:47.380
Well, in general, doing stuff at rock bottom prices to consumers isn't normally a recipe

50:47.380 --> 50:48.500
for massive profitability.

50:48.500 --> 50:53.100
I mean, I know that's a generalization, but it's worth keeping in mind.

50:53.100 --> 51:00.540
And so what's happened is that governments have designed electricity markets and they

51:00.540 --> 51:05.540
have designed the support mechanisms that they provide to renewables operators precisely

51:05.540 --> 51:13.900
in such a way as to maximize the likelihood that the economic gains associated with kind

51:13.900 --> 51:19.460
of falling production costs thanks to China are not captured by nasty capitalist firms,

51:19.460 --> 51:22.740
but they're passed on to consumers.

51:22.740 --> 51:26.380
So what does that mean in terms of capitalist incentives to invest in those things?

51:26.380 --> 51:29.780
Well, if they're not able to capture it, then of course they're not going to do it at the

51:29.780 --> 51:34.940
scale we want because they're being passed on to consumers, which is what we want.

51:34.940 --> 51:39.460
But I mean, there's politicians that don't stay honestly, and it's something I just,

51:39.460 --> 51:42.300
my mind is blown every time I think about it, but it's particularly a problem on the

51:42.300 --> 51:43.300
center left.

51:43.300 --> 51:47.140
But a problem in the center is they genuinely seem to think that private enterprises do

51:47.140 --> 51:48.660
things out of the goodness of their heart.

51:48.660 --> 51:49.660
Yeah.

51:49.660 --> 51:50.660
I mean, it's...

51:50.660 --> 51:51.660
It's just wild.

51:51.660 --> 51:54.140
They want to make lots of money and they want to make as much money as possible.

51:54.140 --> 51:55.140
And here's the other thing, right?

51:55.140 --> 51:56.140
As quickly as possible.

51:57.140 --> 52:01.180
And the other point I would make before we get, before if we want to get into the meat

52:01.180 --> 52:07.580
of it is this, which is that profitability, economic returns are always a relative phenomenon

52:07.580 --> 52:08.860
rather than an absolute phenomenon.

52:08.860 --> 52:15.580
And what I mean by that is that for any capitalist actor, there is always a kind of palette of

52:15.580 --> 52:19.060
different investment opportunities available to them.

52:19.060 --> 52:25.180
And so it's much more, so I give some figures in the book around kind of the average profitability

52:25.220 --> 52:30.540
of renewables deployment, which of course varies across time and space, but most studies

52:30.540 --> 52:34.140
point to somewhere in a region of kind of five to 8% returns.

52:34.140 --> 52:38.380
Now, in isolation, that number doesn't really mean anything.

52:38.380 --> 52:42.380
It only really means anything if you think about the alternative returns that are available

52:42.380 --> 52:44.540
to the relevant actors from doing different things.

52:44.540 --> 52:49.820
Now, and I want to just give two sort of comparators that I think are really valuable

52:49.820 --> 52:51.060
to think about.

52:51.060 --> 52:55.700
The first of those is this, which is to say that five to 8% look pretty good when interest

52:55.700 --> 52:56.980
rates were zero.

52:56.980 --> 53:03.820
But when interest rates are like 5%, and you can get five, six, even 7% returns from sticking

53:03.820 --> 53:11.020
your money in the bank or investing it in US risk-free US government bonds, why on earth

53:11.020 --> 53:19.180
would you go to the hassle of building a wind farm with the major risk that investment entails

53:19.180 --> 53:23.700
when there are risk-free opportunities available to make essentially the same returns?

53:23.700 --> 53:24.700
That's the first comparator.

53:24.700 --> 53:26.020
Really important to think about.

53:26.020 --> 53:31.380
And that's one of the reasons why the industry is really struggling right now is because

53:31.380 --> 53:34.980
of the macroeconomic environment has changed fundamentally in the last couple of years

53:34.980 --> 53:36.980
with the uptick in inflation and interest rates.

53:36.980 --> 53:38.580
So that's the first comparison.

53:38.580 --> 53:43.980
Second comparison is to focus on, you know, perhaps the key constituency that governments

53:43.980 --> 53:51.460
in their wisdom, let me use that word advisedly, have been kind of assuming would take the

53:51.460 --> 53:55.060
lead on the renewable transition, which is the big oil and gas companies.

53:55.060 --> 54:00.100
So they've been hoping that the BP's and the Shells and the Exxons would kind of magically

54:00.100 --> 54:03.860
transition away from oil and gas to offshore wind.

54:03.860 --> 54:10.180
They know how things work offshore, they'll switch their rigs for offshore wind farms.

54:10.180 --> 54:16.300
Well, over the last 10 years or so, those companies have not got out of bed for oil

54:16.300 --> 54:20.620
and gas projects that deliver anything less than 15% returns.

54:20.620 --> 54:23.380
That's what they expect and that's what they get.

54:23.380 --> 54:28.060
And the idea that companies that are used to 15% plus returns in their core business

54:28.060 --> 54:33.620
are somehow going to make the decision to switch to businesses with returns like a third

54:33.620 --> 54:36.420
of that level is absurd.

54:36.420 --> 54:40.500
It's economically madness to think that that's going to happen.

54:40.500 --> 54:45.420
And here's the kicker, as long as they think that those above average returns are going

54:45.420 --> 54:47.540
to continue to be available, right?

