57:48.580 --> 57:52.860
And so you would think, so let's imagine you are a wind energy generator and you've been

57:52.900 --> 57:55.220
in business for like 20 years.

57:55.220 --> 58:01.780
And as your, as your costs go down, you're generating costs go down over time.

58:01.780 --> 58:05.700
Simple economics would say, well, my costs are going down the cost of genera, of actually

58:05.700 --> 58:07.620
generating the power.

58:07.620 --> 58:11.540
So my profits are going to be going up accordingly, fine, you know, lovely jubbly.

58:11.540 --> 58:20.300
But that assumes that you have the capacity to capture and privatize those growing economic

58:20.300 --> 58:21.300
efficiencies.

58:22.300 --> 58:28.020
The reality of the, of the electricity sector is that you now in many, in many, if not most

58:28.020 --> 58:32.820
parts of the world, but certainly in the UK, the electricity generation sector, which is

58:32.820 --> 58:36.740
largely a self-standing sector, it's been cleaved off from transmission and distribution

58:36.740 --> 58:38.060
and retail.

58:38.060 --> 58:44.380
And in particular, the renewable energy generation sector is incredibly competitive.

58:44.380 --> 58:47.540
There are thousands of entities in that market.

58:47.540 --> 58:52.660
They compete purely on price, selling into really, really competitive wholesale markets.

58:52.660 --> 58:59.340
So what happens when price, when, when costs decline, well, they compete those cost gains

58:59.340 --> 59:05.260
away and those cost gains get passed downstream to transmission and distribution entities

59:05.260 --> 59:10.780
and retailers and in large part all the way to consumers, precisely in the way governments

59:10.780 --> 59:12.380
hope they do.

59:12.380 --> 59:18.580
But if generators can't capture and privatize the upsides of those growing cost efficiencies,

59:18.580 --> 59:22.180
why would they invest in their technologies in the first place?

59:22.180 --> 59:25.820
Because they know that because of that competition, I mean, Mark's called it the coercive law

59:25.820 --> 59:27.740
of competition, right?

59:27.740 --> 59:33.140
They're coerced to engage in this activity, but competition forces them to pass those

59:33.140 --> 59:35.100
things downstream.

59:35.100 --> 59:39.500
And we have, you know, in the UK, many people will have heard of the subsidy scheme that

59:39.500 --> 59:46.140
exists for, for wind, for offshore wind, in particular in the UK, which is the contracts

59:46.140 --> 59:47.980
for different scheme.

59:47.980 --> 59:52.180
And as I said earlier, you have this kind of, you have this intensification of competition

59:52.180 --> 59:53.740
which is built into that system.

59:53.740 --> 59:57.700
So it's worth just talking a little bit about how that happens.

59:57.700 --> 01:00:01.100
So if the government says, okay, we're going to award these new offshore wind licenses

01:00:01.100 --> 01:00:06.900
off for new renewables development, what happens is that different generating companies will,

01:00:07.420 --> 01:00:11.660
there's an auction process where effectively what happened is they bid against each other

01:00:11.660 --> 01:00:16.060
for this contract where the government will say, the government or a government backed

01:00:16.060 --> 01:00:21.940
entity says, we will, we, we enter this contract to buy the electricity that you generate at

01:00:21.940 --> 01:00:26.260
a fixed price, essentially a fixed price for the next 12 years or so.

01:00:26.260 --> 01:00:31.820
And so one company will bid for, will bid and say, well, we'll bid, we'll, we'll enter

01:00:31.820 --> 01:00:35.500
that contract with you at 50 pounds per megawatt hour for the next 12 years.

01:00:35.500 --> 01:00:38.300
Another company will say 49, the next one will say 48.

01:00:38.300 --> 01:00:42.620
And essentially what happens is they bid it down until it gets to the point where no one

01:00:42.620 --> 01:00:45.420
can bid any lower because they won't make any money out of it.

01:00:45.420 --> 01:00:50.500
So that's what I mean is that this price based competition is baked into the, is baked into

01:00:50.500 --> 01:00:56.420
the process for good reasons on the consumer side, because that's what you want as a government

01:00:56.420 --> 01:01:01.980
is keeping electricity prices down, but the profit, the potential profitability for generators

01:01:01.980 --> 01:01:03.580
just gets, gets competed away.

01:01:03.660 --> 01:01:06.220
I mean, what you're talking about there with regards to the auctions as well, I mean, it

01:01:06.220 --> 01:01:07.860
applies to outsourcing companies too.

01:01:07.860 --> 01:01:11.820
I mean, the reason why Carillion blasts from the past, you know, they collapse because

