but then you've also said that competition and falling prices are at odds with profitability.

01:04:11.860 --> 01:04:15.820
And if we're having a private market system for this, then you need to have profits.

01:04:15.900 --> 01:04:19.140
So, how do we administer electricity or energy, which is cheap?

01:04:19.140 --> 01:04:20.140
Yeah, it's a great question.

01:04:20.140 --> 01:04:21.620
But from renewable sources too.

01:04:21.620 --> 01:04:23.540
Yeah, it's a great question.

01:04:23.540 --> 01:04:28.820
And I think that, you know, I'll be completely honest about this and say that I don't have

01:04:28.820 --> 01:04:29.820
the answer.

01:04:29.820 --> 01:04:37.140
I think I have a perspective on the range of answers that exists, if that makes sense.

01:04:37.140 --> 01:04:42.060
And so, I think what's useful potentially for viewers is to understand the kind of range

01:04:42.180 --> 01:04:48.780
of main answers that are out there and then to judge for themselves based on some commentary

01:04:48.780 --> 01:04:52.980
that I make on each of those answers.

01:04:52.980 --> 01:04:59.100
And so, there are essentially three main answers out there.

01:04:59.100 --> 01:05:07.420
But I'll caveat this or preface it by saying all of what I'm going to talk about here are

01:05:07.500 --> 01:05:11.660
answers that are kind of on the supply side, by which I mean, they're all answers that

01:05:11.660 --> 01:05:21.060
are oriented towards boosting investment in solar and wind capacity.

01:05:21.060 --> 01:05:28.060
On the assumption that you continue to need to do that because there are those existing

01:05:28.060 --> 01:05:29.860
profitability constraints.

01:05:29.860 --> 01:05:34.340
And of course, there are other answers out there, you know, people who are of a kind

01:05:34.380 --> 01:05:38.140
of degrowth persuasion would say, actually, we need to be thinking about the demand side

01:05:38.140 --> 01:05:41.580
as well and curbing energy consumption.

01:05:41.580 --> 01:05:46.220
And I think that there's a lot of truth in that argument as well.

01:05:46.220 --> 01:05:51.100
But I'm not going to go there today, but clearly any answer that is going to be even close

01:05:51.100 --> 01:05:55.260
to sufficient is going to have to address the supply side and the demand side.

01:05:55.260 --> 01:06:02.140
Also, you know, the other argument will be, hang on a second, we historically globally,

01:06:02.140 --> 01:06:08.580
not just in the West, but globally, in order to try to make renewables more competitive,

01:06:08.580 --> 01:06:15.780
the way we have typically done that is by working on the renewable side, offering subsidy

01:06:15.780 --> 01:06:21.860
mechanisms, support mechanisms on, rather than taxing the dirty side.

01:06:21.860 --> 01:06:23.620
You know, that's essentially what we've done.

01:06:23.620 --> 01:06:26.580
We've thought, OK, we'll do that.

01:06:26.580 --> 01:06:30.500
And so economists, mainstream economists will say, well, actually, the answer is that,

01:06:30.500 --> 01:06:34.260
you know, the externalities associated with fossil fuels are not being properly priced.

01:06:34.260 --> 01:06:39.380
And so the answer is to price those externalities properly.

01:06:39.380 --> 01:06:44.060
And again, I think that I understand that argument, but obviously that's a politically

01:06:44.060 --> 01:06:47.580
very difficult argument because we live such carbon intensive lifestyle.

01:06:47.580 --> 01:06:54.340
So if you start taxing that, it really hurts consumers in terms of inflation.

01:06:54.340 --> 01:06:59.340
And I think that's the main reason why we haven't gone there is that politicians are

01:06:59.340 --> 01:07:01.540
very, very, very concerned about that.

01:07:01.540 --> 01:07:06.740
They don't want consumers to be hurt through higher inflation because of the carnivorous

01:07:06.740 --> 01:07:11.180
nature of the consumer baskets that we all have in our lifestyles.

01:07:11.180 --> 01:07:16.580
So with that said, the three main solutions that are out there in terms of boosting the

01:07:16.580 --> 01:07:22.420
support, you know, boosting the speed of the energy transition on the renewable side are

01:07:22.420 --> 01:07:25.340
and not surprisingly, they're associated with three different kind of interest groups

01:07:25.340 --> 01:07:27.100
for want of a better term.

01:07:27.740 --> 01:07:31.700
And they're all interesting and they all have their merits as well as their drawbacks,

01:07:31.700 --> 01:07:32.700
I think.

01:07:32.700 --> 01:07:37.580
So the first answer is the one that you hear from sort of mainstream energy economists.

01:07:37.580 --> 01:07:43.180
So economists who are trained in orthodox economics and they're focused on energy markets.

01:07:43.180 --> 01:07:47.420
Great people to talk to you because they at least, unlike a lot of my colleagues on the

01:07:47.420 --> 01:07:53.140
left know the energy markets, they really know what they're talking about there, although

01:07:53.140 --> 01:07:57.220
they look at them through certain in certain blinked ways, I would argue.

01:07:57.220 --> 01:08:02.500
So what they argue is, look, the problem is not that we're relying on the private sector

01:08:02.500 --> 01:08:06.780
and the profit motive and markets to do this, of course, they wouldn't, they don't say that.

01:08:06.780 --> 01:08:07.780
That's fine.

01:08:07.780 --> 01:08:12.180
What they argue is that the problem is that the market design is not right.

01:08:12.180 --> 01:08:17.580
So what they would say is that, is that, and I have some sympathy with this argument because

01:08:17.620 --> 01:08:24.420
they're right when they say that electricity markets as they exist worldwide today are market

01:08:24.420 --> 01:08:29.860
mechanisms that were designed essentially in a fossil fuel world and they haven't really

01:08:29.860 --> 01:08:32.660
been changed in the last 20, 30, and that's true.

01:08:32.660 --> 01:08:33.660
They haven't.

01:08:33.660 --> 01:08:36.380
They're pretty much the way they've always been.

01:08:36.380 --> 01:08:41.420
And they argue and it's understandable, they say, look, we just need to redesign those

01:08:41.420 --> 01:08:46.380
market mechanisms, rethink the way we price electricity and wholesale and retail markets,

01:08:46.380 --> 01:08:49.180
and then everything will fall magically into place.

01:08:49.180 --> 01:08:53.260
But of course, economists always say that, that's the answer to every problem, which

01:08:53.260 --> 01:08:57.420
is that the problem with markets is not that we have markets, the problem is that we haven't

01:08:57.420 --> 01:08:58.420
got them right yet.

01:08:58.420 --> 01:08:59.420
We haven't perfected them.

01:08:59.420 --> 01:09:02.340
We haven't optimised them.

01:09:02.340 --> 01:09:06.540
And also there are lots of recommendations out there circulating in different forums

01:09:06.540 --> 01:09:08.740
for how you might do that.

01:09:08.740 --> 01:09:14.300
But all of them have distinctive drawbacks as well as potential advantages associated

01:09:14.300 --> 01:09:15.300
with them.

01:09:15.700 --> 01:09:16.700
That's that answer.

01:09:16.700 --> 01:09:19.940
And as I said, I have some sympathy with that argument, but I'm definitely not convinced

01:09:19.940 --> 01:09:20.940
by it.

01:09:20.940 --> 01:09:23.220
The second answer is, again, is very, very interesting.

01:09:23.220 --> 01:09:28.940
And that's the answer you typically hear from the energy industry itself.

01:09:28.940 --> 01:09:33.140
And so what they say, obviously they agree with economists that the problem is not that

01:09:33.140 --> 01:09:37.420
we're relying on the private sector markets, but where they disagree largely with economists

01:09:37.420 --> 01:09:40.460
is they don't think the problem is in market design.

01:09:40.460 --> 01:09:42.060
They say, no, that's fine as well.

01:09:42.060 --> 01:09:44.980
Just keep existing markets as they are.

01:09:44.980 --> 01:09:48.100
The problem is that the subsidies to renewables aren't big enough.

01:09:48.100 --> 01:09:53.740
So they basically say, look, keep everything as it is, but just like double the support

01:09:53.740 --> 01:09:57.980
mechanisms may provide more of it and make them more attractive.

01:09:57.980 --> 01:10:02.700
And that's what the Inflation Reduction Act was in the renewable sector.

