provide us with lowering the level of tax credit.

01:10:13.540 --> 01:10:14.700
And it's stagnating.

01:10:14.700 --> 01:10:17.260
That's what you get if you do that.

01:10:17.260 --> 01:10:18.260
Lift it back up.

01:10:18.260 --> 01:10:19.860
And so that's what the government did.

01:10:19.860 --> 01:10:21.980
We get to see whether that will have the desired impact.

01:10:21.980 --> 01:10:28.420
But that was, in my view, was all about re-inflating profitability in the renewables industry to

01:10:28.420 --> 01:10:33.980
re-attract investment into that sector, very, very straightforward actually.

01:10:33.980 --> 01:10:42.300
And I have some sympathy with that as well, because if the totality of our options is the

01:10:42.300 --> 01:10:46.900
private sector, what else are you going to do?

01:10:46.900 --> 01:10:49.100
That would work, is what you're saying, in your opinion.

01:10:49.100 --> 01:10:50.460
I think it probably would.

01:10:50.460 --> 01:10:57.100
If you essentially guarantee profits, and if those profits are attractive in relative

01:10:57.100 --> 01:11:02.060
terms according to the different alternatives that are out there, then, yeah, money will

01:11:02.060 --> 01:11:03.060
flow in.

01:11:03.060 --> 01:11:04.060
Absolutely.

01:11:04.060 --> 01:11:11.420
I mean, it would be really costly for the consumer and or the taxpayer in some combination.

01:11:11.420 --> 01:11:14.140
But I think it would work if the government did that enough.

01:11:14.140 --> 01:11:18.020
But obviously, there's huge reluctance to do that for all sorts of reasons.

01:11:18.020 --> 01:11:21.180
Not just the cost to the consumer, you don't want to see it be seen to be lining the pockets

01:11:21.180 --> 01:11:23.740
of nasty big capital.

01:11:23.740 --> 01:11:24.740
That's the second option.

01:11:24.740 --> 01:11:31.140
The third option is the one that those on the left will typically say, which is to say,

01:11:31.140 --> 01:11:34.260
the problem is that we're relying on the private sector and markets to do this.

01:11:34.260 --> 01:11:35.740
It doesn't work.

01:11:35.740 --> 01:11:41.140
We've been doing it for 30 years, still isn't working, still going much too slowly.

01:11:41.180 --> 01:11:47.180
Let's try something different by which they normally mean, or we, if I count myself in

01:11:47.180 --> 01:11:57.260
this group, normally mean mass public sector ownership and investment in renewable energy.

01:11:57.260 --> 01:12:00.700
The argument being that the private sector and markets isn't working, isn't being shown

01:12:00.700 --> 01:12:07.820
not to be working, even though that all these subsidies continue to be available worldwide.

01:12:07.900 --> 01:12:15.700
That's a really, in many ways, at least on the face of things, a very attractive option.

01:12:15.700 --> 01:12:19.700
If you think about it like this, so go back to what I was saying earlier about five to

01:12:19.700 --> 01:12:25.220
eight percent returns, well, if five percent, eight percent returns are not sufficiently

01:12:25.220 --> 01:12:30.940
attractive to draw in mass private sector investment on a significant scale, you would

01:12:30.940 --> 01:12:35.060
imagine that returns of five to eight percent would be perfectly attractive for the public

01:12:35.060 --> 01:12:36.060
sector.

01:12:36.820 --> 01:12:41.940
Presumably, if you are a government, you would just be happy with an investment that kind

01:12:41.940 --> 01:12:47.740
of covers the cost of capital, and if it doesn't do any more than fine, why would you need

01:12:47.740 --> 01:12:49.500
any more than that?

01:12:49.500 --> 01:12:58.540
In principle, I think that that is a very attractive option, but of course, there are

01:12:58.540 --> 01:13:05.300
obstacles of all sorts of different nature, of an ideological nature, clearly.

01:13:05.300 --> 01:13:12.740
The fact that the idea that the private sector can't or shouldn't do this is anathema to

01:13:12.740 --> 01:13:22.140
the political class in large parts, not just of the West, but of the world more generally.

01:13:22.140 --> 01:13:29.460
Governments around the world, including in what, by global standards, are rich countries,

01:13:29.460 --> 01:13:34.140
have persuaded themselves or allowed themselves to be persuaded that they don't have the fiscal

01:13:34.180 --> 01:13:38.820
capacity to carry out that type of investment, they need to be fiscally conservative, it's

01:13:38.820 --> 01:13:43.580
all about tightening belts, you can't grow the public balance sheet, even if it is to

01:13:43.580 --> 01:13:47.900
invest in revenue-generating assets, and I don't really buy those arguments, but those

01:13:47.900 --> 01:13:54.980
arguments are very, very powerful, and it seems right now, at least, that very few mainstream

01:13:54.980 --> 01:13:59.700
parties at least are even willing to count on any departure from that kind of economic

01:13:59.700 --> 01:14:00.700
orthodoxy.

01:14:01.260 --> 01:14:08.540
So, while I think that it's a credible proposition for rich countries, it doesn't seem very likely

01:14:08.540 --> 01:14:10.220
that it's going to be happening any time soon.

01:14:10.220 --> 01:14:15.540
Any talk of public sector ownership of energy in places like the UK is, any propositions

01:14:15.540 --> 01:14:18.660
along those lines are very, very limited, very, very small scale.

01:14:18.660 --> 01:14:20.220
Stam has killed it, right?

01:14:20.220 --> 01:14:21.220
Basically, yeah.

01:14:21.220 --> 01:14:26.700
It means overtly saying, this will be the market, we're not the Tories, but it will be the market.

01:14:27.420 --> 01:14:31.500
Which means that, as we were talking about earlier, great British energy such as it is,

01:14:31.500 --> 01:14:35.060
or such as it might be, what's the point?

01:14:35.060 --> 01:14:40.300
It's going to be a bit-part player in a private market that is completely unchanged, so it

01:14:40.300 --> 01:14:43.220
will just be like another private sector player, basically, and it probably won't even do it

01:14:43.220 --> 01:14:45.620
as well as those in the private sector.

01:14:45.620 --> 01:14:49.460
What's the point of doing it on a small scale if you're not doing something fundamentally

01:14:49.460 --> 01:14:50.460
different?

01:14:50.460 --> 01:14:54.940
There's no point, in my view, there's literally no point in public sector ownership unless

01:14:55.180 --> 01:15:00.660
you are enabling and incentivising that actor to do something fundamentally differently

01:15:00.660 --> 01:15:01.660
from a private sector.

01:15:01.660 --> 01:15:03.860
Otherwise, there's no point, just let the private sector do it.

01:15:03.860 --> 01:15:06.860
It's going to be a private sector actor which pays shit wages to people.

01:15:06.860 --> 01:15:07.860
Probably.

01:15:07.860 --> 01:15:08.860
And does a shit job.

01:15:08.860 --> 01:15:09.860
Yeah, that's what's going to happen.

01:15:09.860 --> 01:15:10.860
Yeah, of course.

01:15:10.860 --> 01:15:13.980
Best case scenario, it will be mediocre market actor and it will be privatised by the Tories

01:15:13.980 --> 01:15:14.980
in 15 years.

01:15:14.980 --> 01:15:15.980
That's what's going to happen.

01:15:15.980 --> 01:15:16.980
Best case scenario.

01:15:16.980 --> 01:15:17.980
100%.

01:15:17.980 --> 01:15:18.980
Yeah.

01:15:18.980 --> 01:15:19.980
There's no point.

01:15:19.980 --> 01:15:24.420
Unless you're going to do it on a large scale with the ambition to do something fundamentally

01:15:24.420 --> 01:15:27.420
differently, there's no point in doing it in my view.

01:15:27.420 --> 01:15:31.300
The only argument for doing it would be that it's like a wedge in the door and that then

01:15:31.300 --> 01:15:34.620
you can build on it potentially.

01:15:34.620 --> 01:15:39.940
Maybe that's the grand plan that's not being talked about, but I'm doubtful anyway.

01:15:39.940 --> 01:15:42.580
But the other thing about public sector ownership, I think, the only other thing I would like

01:15:42.580 --> 01:15:52.620
to say about that is that even if it is theoretically, to my mind, quite credible and possible in

01:15:52.620 --> 01:15:56.540
the relatively rich parts of the world, it's a different matter entirely in going back to

01:15:56.540 --> 01:15:58.460
where we started our conversation.

01:15:58.460 --> 01:16:04.980
In those parts of the world where investment is most vital, if you're talking about those

01:16:04.980 --> 01:16:10.100
countries in the global south that we were talking about, the idea that governments in

01:16:10.100 --> 01:16:18.900
those parts of the world, which are struggling under infinitely more severe fiscal constraints

01:16:18.900 --> 01:16:24.780
than the governments of the US or Germany or the UK, are going to kind of borrow cheaply

01:16:24.780 --> 01:16:31.420
on the capital markets for investment in public ownership of renewables, ain't going to happen.

01:16:31.420 --> 01:16:36.340
You could say we're going to recalibrate the provider of the World Bank and so it's not

01:16:36.340 --> 01:16:39.260
like implausible, but it's not going to happen right now.

01:16:39.260 --> 01:16:40.260
No.

01:16:40.260 --> 01:16:41.260
It's definitely not going to happen right now.

01:16:41.260 --> 01:16:47.100
But you would need to give it insofar as the fact that, for example, many of those

01:16:47.100 --> 01:16:55.580
countries are kind of staggering under huge existing debt servicing obligations from the

01:16:55.580 --> 01:17:02.300
past, those would have to just be written off essentially in order to enable that kind

01:17:02.300 --> 01:17:04.300
of new investment to take place.

01:17:04.300 --> 01:17:08.300
So it's a big ask politically as well as economically.

01:17:08.300 --> 01:17:10.860
Speaking of the kind of austerity arrangements, and I find this quite funny, it's a bit of

01:17:10.860 --> 01:17:18.260
a tangent, but you have in Europe with the Eurozone and European monetary integration,

01:17:18.260 --> 01:17:22.820
you've had since 1999, since there's been the Euro as a currency, the stability and

01:17:22.820 --> 01:17:27.540
growth pact, which all the members of the European Union actually, I think, have to

01:17:27.540 --> 01:17:32.420
adhere to, one of the major parts of that is to not run deficits of more than 3%.

01:17:32.420 --> 01:17:35.660
Now of course, if your economy is growing at 3%, 4% and you've got inflation of 3%,

01:17:35.660 --> 01:17:40.980
4%, a deficit of 3% forever is absolutely fine actually.

01:17:40.980 --> 01:17:44.940
But what's really interesting is they suspended it in 2020, I don't know if you saw the story,

01:17:44.940 --> 01:17:50.780
they suspended it in 2020, and it's only going to come back now, I think it was 2020 to 2023.

01:17:50.780 --> 01:17:56.980
And over that time frame, Italy's GDP per capita grows quickly as the United States,

01:17:56.980 --> 01:18:00.460
because there was loads of public sector investment in really important infrastructure.

01:18:00.460 --> 01:18:05.620
And now the European Union is saying to Italy, you can't run deficits anymore, and if you

01:18:05.620 --> 01:18:09.100
don't, we'll sanction you, and you think, fuck, they've just literally been growing

01:18:09.100 --> 01:18:14.100
at their best clip in 25 years, but their stupid little brains can't get around it.

01:18:14.100 --> 01:18:20.060
On the point you said about public ownership, and again, it's like an ideological default

01:18:20.060 --> 01:18:22.740
now, which people do not understand.

01:18:22.740 --> 01:18:24.540
The idea of public ownership making money.

01:18:24.540 --> 01:18:25.540
Absolutely.

01:18:25.540 --> 01:18:29.580
It's only going to be us sinking money, losing money.

01:18:29.580 --> 01:18:32.380
You're talking about investing in revenue generating assets.

01:18:32.380 --> 01:18:33.380
What's the problem with that?

01:18:33.380 --> 01:18:36.460
I mean, if you look at, for instance, where I live, Portsmouth, I did an article about

01:18:36.460 --> 01:18:41.220
this recently, you've got Portsmouth International Port, which was built in the early 1970s.

01:18:41.220 --> 01:18:47.540
The idea of a city, a medium sized city like Portsmouth, building infrastructure like that

01:18:47.540 --> 01:18:51.620
today in partnership with the private sector is just like implausible.

01:18:51.620 --> 01:18:55.260
So they built Portsmouth International Port, I think it adds a couple of hundred million

01:18:55.260 --> 01:18:58.420
to the national economy, it employs 5,000 people.

01:18:58.420 --> 01:19:00.500
Last year it made eight million pound profit.

01:19:00.500 --> 01:19:02.780
It's publicly owned, right?

01:19:02.780 --> 01:19:07.800
And basically, since it's been built and it's not been privatized, that has basically

01:19:07.800 --> 01:19:11.460
meant hundreds of millions of pounds going to local people in Portsmouth.

01:19:11.460 --> 01:19:14.660
It means lower council tax and it's paid for a ton of services.

01:19:14.660 --> 01:19:20.220
Up there in Southampton, where the airport's privatized, guess what, the city's busts.

01:19:20.220 --> 01:19:25.940
But people were spending too much, or maybe actually it's about ownership and you're

01:19:25.940 --> 01:19:27.740
not owning the things that make cash.

01:19:27.740 --> 01:19:28.740
100%.

01:19:28.740 --> 01:19:31.820
And there are two things I would add to that.

01:19:31.820 --> 01:19:38.580
One of them is, you mentioned parenthetically, which is, you said it's built by the public

01:19:38.580 --> 01:19:40.700
sector in collaboration with the private sector.

01:19:40.700 --> 01:19:43.540
So lots of people, when you talk about public sector ownership of energy, they say, well,

01:19:43.540 --> 01:19:46.500
the public sector can't do that, public sector doesn't have the capacity and the expertise.

01:19:46.500 --> 01:19:49.900
You don't have to build it yourself, you just give a contract to someone to the private

01:19:49.900 --> 01:19:50.900
sector to build it.

01:19:50.900 --> 01:19:54.660
It's the ownership that matters, you don't have to build it, it's the capacity.

01:19:54.660 --> 01:19:58.460
And then the second thing is, they're like, well, then the public sector will fuck up

01:19:58.460 --> 01:19:59.460
the operation.

01:19:59.460 --> 01:20:02.340
Or a wind and solar farm doesn't take much operation.

01:20:02.340 --> 01:20:05.140
Once they're built, you don't have to do anything.

01:20:05.140 --> 01:20:09.060
Occasionally a rotor will stop turning and you have to send an engineer out with a screwdriver

01:20:09.060 --> 01:20:10.220
to get it going again.

01:20:10.220 --> 01:20:11.580
But that's about it.

01:20:11.580 --> 01:20:14.380
It doesn't take like a rocket scientist to run a wind or solar farm.

01:20:14.380 --> 01:20:18.380
So the idea that the public sector can't do this is preposterous.

01:20:18.380 --> 01:20:21.740
And I think about Southampton up the road.

01:20:21.740 --> 01:20:27.020
Like I say, their bust, they're dimmed street lights in Southampton, like 20%.

01:20:27.020 --> 01:20:32.580
They're going off an hour earlier and you think you've got the country's second biggest

01:20:32.580 --> 01:20:37.900
commercial port after Felix, though, and it's in private hands and you're turning off the

01:20:37.900 --> 01:20:39.300
fucking lights an hour earlier.

01:20:39.300 --> 01:20:41.660
Like this is a madhouse.

01:20:41.660 --> 01:20:45.500
Many people in Pompey would say Southampton's a madhouse, but for very different reasons.

01:20:45.500 --> 01:20:47.860
They probably lose to their football team next year as well.

01:20:47.860 --> 01:20:49.700
Well, Southampton might get promoted.

01:20:49.700 --> 01:20:50.700
Oh yeah, they're in the final.

01:20:50.700 --> 01:20:51.700
Good point.

01:20:51.700 --> 01:20:52.700
They might get promoted.

01:20:52.700 --> 01:20:55.540
I don't want them to get promoted for people who aren't aware, but Portsmouth has just been

01:20:55.580 --> 01:21:00.300
promoted to the championship and thanks to our in that league as well.

01:21:00.300 --> 01:21:03.700
So I mean, that to me is interesting, the idea of public ownership or something, which

01:21:03.700 --> 01:21:07.260
is going to make money, which, you know, again, a lot of the public doesn't understand that.

01:21:07.260 --> 01:21:09.980
It's not because the public are daft, it's because literally no politician other than

01:21:09.980 --> 01:21:15.300
Jeremy Corbyn has actually even made tried to make the argument for 30 years, but it seems

01:21:15.300 --> 01:21:16.580
to me like you're saying...

01:21:16.580 --> 01:21:19.140
And Bernie Sanders in the US made the exact same argument.

01:21:19.140 --> 01:21:24.820
We can have public ownership with a decent rate of return, really good social externalities

01:21:24.900 --> 01:21:25.820
as they be called.

01:21:25.820 --> 01:21:26.820
Yeah.

01:21:26.820 --> 01:21:27.820
Yeah.

01:21:27.820 --> 01:21:28.820
Decarbonizing.

01:21:28.820 --> 01:21:29.820
What's the problem?

01:21:29.820 --> 01:21:30.820
So what is the problem?

01:21:30.820 --> 01:21:31.820
Well, I think it's ideological.

01:21:31.820 --> 01:21:34.100
I mean, I think, I think that's, that's what it is.

01:21:34.100 --> 01:21:36.900
But there's no special interest groups stopping them from doing that.

01:21:36.900 --> 01:21:37.900
In the globe.

01:21:37.900 --> 01:21:42.060
No, no, I don't think, I mean, except for the fact that, of course, behind the scenes,

01:21:42.060 --> 01:21:48.020
the energy sector, the asset managers and so on, are telling them that they can't do

01:21:48.020 --> 01:21:51.940
it for all those reasons that we've, that we've touched on already.

01:21:52.060 --> 01:21:56.860
So it's not just, I mean, ideology is kind of created by interest groups to a significant

01:21:56.860 --> 01:22:02.780
extent, but I don't think they, I don't think there are substantive economic arguments against

01:22:02.780 --> 01:22:05.140
it in, in certain countries of the world.

01:22:05.140 --> 01:22:11.180
And I think that it's much more challenging in parts of the world where, you know, absent

01:22:11.180 --> 01:22:19.060
really significant transformations, but certainly in a place like the UK, it's completely, completely

01:22:19.060 --> 01:22:20.060
credible.

01:22:20.180 --> 01:22:21.180
Okay.

01:22:21.180 --> 01:22:23.260
So it's public ownership, but it's public ownership without conflict.

01:22:23.260 --> 01:22:26.540
It's not like you're saying, right, we're going to bring this stuff into public ownership.

01:22:26.540 --> 01:22:28.700
It's literally saying, okay, well, we're going to build new capacity in the state.

01:22:28.700 --> 01:22:29.700
It's going to do it in the state.

01:22:29.700 --> 01:22:30.700
We'll own it.

01:22:30.700 --> 01:22:31.700
Yeah.

01:22:31.700 --> 01:22:33.940
You're not saying, okay, well, these water companies, they're, they're screwing up, they've

01:22:33.940 --> 01:22:36.820
failed, screw them, because of course, their counter-argument is where your bills are going

01:22:36.820 --> 01:22:37.820
to go up.

01:22:37.820 --> 01:22:38.820
Right.

01:22:38.820 --> 01:22:41.100
So it's, it's, it seems like a very low cost form of public ownership.

01:22:41.100 --> 01:22:42.100
I think so.

01:22:42.100 --> 01:22:43.100
Yeah.

01:22:43.100 --> 01:22:44.100
No, I think so.

01:22:44.140 --> 01:22:51.580
I think that, that's, that's where the kind of really interesting arguments are coming

01:22:51.580 --> 01:22:52.580
from.

01:22:52.580 --> 01:22:57.220
And, and, and there are some, some initiatives in that direction, not in the UK, but in, in,

01:22:57.220 --> 01:23:01.020
in New York state, many people might have heard the, there's, there was a build public

01:23:01.020 --> 01:23:07.100
renewables act that was passed last year, I think it was, which at least on paper looks

01:23:07.100 --> 01:23:12.420
like it could be quite significant in terms of public ownership of electricity generation,

01:23:13.420 --> 01:23:18.860
in New York state remains to be seen whether it will actually be actioned in significant

01:23:18.860 --> 01:23:19.860
part.

01:23:19.860 --> 01:23:25.340
You know, the, the, the, the degree to, you know, just because it's there on paper doesn't

01:23:25.340 --> 01:23:29.020
necessarily mean it's actually going to, going to happen on the ground.

01:23:29.020 --> 01:23:34.220
There are, there are lots of potential obstacles in the way of a political nature, but things

01:23:34.220 --> 01:23:35.580
are happening on that front.

01:23:35.580 --> 01:23:39.220
So there is reason, there is reason for hope, I think, on that front.

01:23:39.220 --> 01:23:44.940
But I, you know, I think that of, of the three kind of options I outlined, that seems to

01:23:44.940 --> 01:23:52.540
me at least, to be the one with the most potential, to get things, to get things going more quickly

01:23:52.540 --> 01:23:53.660
than they currently are.

01:23:53.660 --> 01:23:59.940
And that's the thing, that's the thing right is like every year matters on this, because

01:23:59.940 --> 01:24:04.620
you know, every, every year with emissions that are higher than they need to be means

01:24:04.620 --> 01:24:08.700
that extra little bit of carbon in the atmosphere or extra large bit of carbon in the atmosphere.

01:24:09.260 --> 01:24:11.340
I just want to go back to something we were talking about earlier on.

01:24:11.340 --> 01:24:15.380
I mentioned Scotland, which actually in terms of the percentage of electricity coming from

01:24:15.380 --> 01:24:17.420
renewables is really impressive.

01:24:17.420 --> 01:24:18.420
Yes.

01:24:18.420 --> 01:24:19.660
And you said you want to talk about Scotland more.

01:24:19.660 --> 01:24:20.660
Yes.

01:24:20.660 --> 01:24:21.660
Please go ahead.

01:24:21.660 --> 01:24:22.660
Good point.

01:24:22.660 --> 01:24:23.900
I'd forgotten about that, but very, very good point.

01:24:23.900 --> 01:24:28.460
So here's the interesting, here's the interesting thing and this, this, this point about the

01:24:28.460 --> 01:24:32.940
geography of renewables, which is what I'm going to talk about, bears directly on that

01:24:32.940 --> 01:24:33.940
question of profitability.

01:24:33.940 --> 01:24:38.420
We were talking about earlier this, this kind of paradox of why renewables deployment

01:24:38.420 --> 01:24:41.580
is not as profitable as people think it might be.

01:24:41.580 --> 01:24:43.820
And part of the answer is the geography of this.

01:24:43.820 --> 01:24:50.460
So in the UK, but not just in the UK, pretty much anywhere in the world you look, it's

01:24:50.460 --> 01:24:53.780
the same in Sweden where I live, it's the same in China, it's the same in India and

01:24:53.780 --> 01:24:59.900
also in Germany and the US, the, the, the recurring geographical feature that you see

01:24:59.900 --> 01:25:07.260
about renewables is that wind and solar facilities tend to be located at the opposite ends of

01:25:07.260 --> 01:25:10.740
the country to where most people live and most industry is located.

01:25:10.740 --> 01:25:15.020
So in the, in, in Sweden, for example, the population is disproportionately located

01:25:15.020 --> 01:25:21.220
in the south and all the wind power is up in the north, exactly the same in the UK.

01:25:21.220 --> 01:25:24.860
Now there are two important things to, to understand about that.

01:25:24.860 --> 01:25:28.020
Firstly is, is, is why that happens.

01:25:28.020 --> 01:25:34.140
And then the second thing is what the implications are there, are there of that for the profitability

01:25:34.140 --> 01:25:36.100
of renewables generators.

01:25:36.100 --> 01:25:39.460
So why it happens, it happens for all sorts of different reasons.

01:25:39.460 --> 01:25:44.500
And in the UK case, there are certain physical reasons about wind speeds and stuff like that.

01:25:44.500 --> 01:25:49.340
But the main reason that happens everywhere is, is, is precisely because that's where

01:25:49.340 --> 01:25:51.040
people don't live.

01:25:51.040 --> 01:25:56.220
And if you are developing a wind or solar farm, one of your biggest costs is likely

01:25:56.220 --> 01:25:59.500
to be land, is likely to be land costs, right?

01:25:59.500 --> 01:26:03.520
Unlike conventional power plants, wind and solar facilities take up a huge amount of

01:26:03.520 --> 01:26:04.520
land.

01:26:04.520 --> 01:26:07.400
If you're going to be generating a lot of power, it's a huge amount of land.

01:26:07.400 --> 01:26:12.160
And so all other things being equal, developers of renewables projects always will try to

01:26:12.160 --> 01:26:16.280
cite their facilities where land is cheapest.

01:26:16.280 --> 01:26:21.960
So take the, take the US case, for example, you know, the cost of land in, in, you know,

01:26:21.960 --> 01:26:28.160
the northwest in, in, in, in Montana or something like that is like 1% of the cost in the east

01:26:28.160 --> 01:26:29.160
coast.

01:26:29.160 --> 01:26:33.360
So of course you're going to put your facility there because your land cost is cheaper.

01:26:33.360 --> 01:26:38.440
And land costs, the cost of leasing or buy it, a part of that generating costs we talked

01:26:38.440 --> 01:26:41.360
about earlier, that's, that's factored into that generating costs.

01:26:41.360 --> 01:26:45.440
So the fact, those generating costs that come down so much, that includes land costs.

01:26:45.440 --> 01:26:48.960
So that's why you get this geographical pattern.

01:26:48.960 --> 01:26:51.200
Now what does that mean in terms of profitability?

01:26:51.200 --> 01:26:58.200
Well, the thing is, is that if, if your facilities are located a very, very far away on average

01:26:58.200 --> 01:27:05.480
from where the demand for that electricity is concentrated, then your facility is, is,

01:27:05.480 --> 01:27:11.600
is, is, is exerting a disproportionate burden on the grid, on the, on the transmission and

01:27:11.600 --> 01:27:19.800
distribution grid, because it's much more, you are, you are basically, it's much more

01:27:19.800 --> 01:27:24.960
expensive to maintain a grid over long distances, obviously, than over short distances.

01:27:24.960 --> 01:27:28.800
And the way that this works is that, is that grid operators, those that run the grid in

01:27:28.800 --> 01:27:34.480
any case of the national grid in the UK, it, for the cost, that for all the costs of maintaining

01:27:34.480 --> 01:27:39.400
that grid and upgrading it and improving it and adding to it, those costs are borne by

01:27:39.400 --> 01:27:44.880
everyone who's part of, of the system, both on the consumption side and on the demand

01:27:44.880 --> 01:27:45.880
side.

01:27:45.880 --> 01:27:49.840
So on the consumption side, you at home and you pay your electricity bill, you are paying

01:27:49.840 --> 01:27:54.000
for electricity to be generated, but you're also paying for it to be transported.

01:27:54.000 --> 01:27:57.320
So your share of the grid costs, essentially, to where you live.

01:27:57.320 --> 01:27:59.840
But generators are also charged for that.

01:27:59.840 --> 01:28:06.760
And while they're not necessarily charged perfectly based on where they, where they

01:28:06.760 --> 01:28:13.680
are based, but in general, they are charged much more the further they are away from where

01:28:13.680 --> 01:28:15.640
demand for electricity is located.

01:28:15.640 --> 01:28:21.240
So, renewables developers are essentially, because they're much more further away on

01:28:21.240 --> 01:28:24.560
average in conventional power plants from where their electricity demand is located,

01:28:24.560 --> 01:28:27.840
they have much higher transportation costs.

01:28:27.840 --> 01:28:31.640
So the thing is, right, when, when those, those people focus on, when, when the analysts

01:28:31.640 --> 01:28:37.920
focus on generating costs, low cost of renewables, it's actually a completely artificial cost

01:28:37.920 --> 01:28:41.320
because it excludes those transportation costs.

01:28:41.320 --> 01:28:42.440
And you can even say it better than that.

01:28:42.440 --> 01:28:47.840
You can say the generating costs are only low because the transportation costs are high.

01:28:47.840 --> 01:28:49.200
Do you see what I mean?

01:28:49.240 --> 01:28:53.800
It's like you only have low generating costs because you have low land costs and you only

01:28:53.800 --> 01:28:58.800
have low land costs because you're a million miles away from where the demand is located.

01:28:58.800 --> 01:29:02.320
So you're going to have a huge burden on their transmission system and high transmission

01:29:02.320 --> 01:29:03.520
charges.

01:29:03.520 --> 01:29:06.880
So you may think that you're going to be really profitable because you're, because you're

01:29:06.880 --> 01:29:12.080
generating costs are very low, but your transportation costs, which no one ever talks about, are

01:29:12.080 --> 01:29:13.080
really, really high.

01:29:13.080 --> 01:29:18.080
So the geography of this, the economic geography of electricity is unbelievably important.

